>what is meant by OIDC and how we can give access to the cluster if it is on premises cluster how can we maintain the OIDC authentication?
    >>OIDC (OpenID Connect) is an identity layer built on top of OAuth 2.0.
It allows applications (like Kubernetes) to authenticate users via an external Identity Provider (IdP).
👉 In simple words:
OIDC lets Kubernetes trust an external login system (SSO) to verify users instead of using client certificates.\
Kubernetes does not manage human users internally.
OIDC enables Kubernetes to authenticate users via:

Username
Groups
Email
Claims from an external IdP
User → Identity Provider → Token (JWT) → API Server → RBAC
User logs in to IdP (browser / CLI plugin)
IdP authenticates user (password, MFA, LDAP, etc.)
IdP issues OIDC ID Token (JWT)
kubectl sends token to Kubernetes API
API server:

Validates token signature
Verifies issuer & audience
API server extracts:
username
groups
RBAC decides access
OIDC in Kubernetes allows authentication via an external identity provider, and for an on‑prem cluster it is implemented by 
    deploying an OIDC provider (like Keycloak), configuring the API server to trust it, and using RBAC to authorize users based on token claims.


